At this point, white has an advantage in space.  Your d and e pawns control the center -- c5, d5, e5, and f5.
You should have played Nf3, but d5 is also ok. Generally speaking, the tension you had before d5 was working in your favor.  The player who breaks that tension usually suffers by doing so.

Why not Qc2?  You get your queen off the back rank and threaten the pawn on c4. Actually, f3 is a mistake (not a blunder). You hinder the development of your knight and your bishop. Ne2 closes you bishop in, unless of course you take the pawn on c4.

What were your thoughts here?  This is a big boo-boo. Black should have played Nxd5 and you would have played Bxc8 and then Nxd4 and then Be7 and then Nxa2+ and you're a goner.
This is one of black's bigger mistakes!  You could have clawed back into it by playing Qa3.  Next for black would have been Qb6, Bb3, h6, Bxf6, Qxf6 and you still have a chance.
Qxa5 is not worth your time.  Qb1 and then c4 would have been better.
